# Quantitative Finance Roadmap: From Beginner to Expert

## Table of Contents
1. Introduction
2. Beginner Level
- Mathematics for Quantitative Finance
- Programming for Quantitative Finance
- Financial Markets & Instruments
3. Intermediate Level
- Quantitative Trading Strategies
- Machine Learning in Finance
- Derivatives Pricing & Risk Management
4. Advanced Level
- Portfolio Optimization
- Fixed Income & Credit Risk Modeling
- Alternative Data & AI in Quant Trading
5. Career Preparation
- Industry Certifications
- Networking & Job Search
6. Specialization & Research
7. Resources

---

## Introduction
This roadmap provides a step-by-step guide for mastering quantitative finance, starting from foundational concepts to advanced topics in trading, risk management, and machine learning.

---

## Beginner Level
### Mathematics for Quantitative Finance
Topics:
- Linear Algebra: Matrices, Eigenvalues, Eigenvectors, Singular Value Decomposition (SVD)
- Calculus: Differentiation, Integration, Multivariable Calculus, Optimization
- Probability & Statistics: Bayes‚Äô Theorem, Distributions, Hypothesis Testing
- Stochastic Calculus: Brownian Motion, Ito‚Äôs Lemma
- Convex Optimization (important for portfolio optimization)
- Fourier Transforms (used in option pricing and signal processing for quant strategies)

Resources:
- "Mathematics for Finance: An Introduction to Financial Engineering" ‚Äì Marek Capinski & Tomasz Zastawniak
- MIT OpenCourseWare - Probability & Statistics (MIT OCW)

### Programming for Quantitative Finance
Topics:
- Python: NumPy, Pandas, SciPy, Matplotlib, Statsmodels
- C++: STL, Multithreading, Memory Management
- SQL: Querying financial datasets
- Java (used in trading infrastructure)
- R (for statistical modeling)
- Cython (for performance optimization in Python-based quant models)
- Rust (gaining popularity in HFT due to safety and speed)

Resources:
- "Python for Finance" ‚Äì Yves Hilpisch
- QuantStart - Learn Python for Quant Finance (QuantStart)

### Financial Markets & Instruments
Topics:
- Financial Instruments: Equities, Bonds, Options, Futures, Swaps
- Market Microstructure: Bid-Ask Spread, Order Books
- Portfolio & Risk Management
- Market Efficiency Theories (Efficient Market Hypothesis, Behavioral Finance)
- Microstructure Analysis: Market-making, limit order book dynamics
- Fixed Income Derivatives (Interest Rate Swaps, Swaptions, Bond Futures, Bond Pricing Models (Discounted Cash Flow, Yield to Maturity, Duration & Convexity) (document)

Resources:
- "Options, Futures, and Other Derivatives" ‚Äì John Hull
- Coursera - Financial Markets by Yale (Coursera)

---

## Intermediate Level
### Quantitative Trading Strategies
Topics:
- Time Series Analysis: ARIMA, GARCH models
- Statistical Arbitrage: Cointegration, Mean Reversion
- Monte Carlo Simulations for risk & pricing models
- Pairs Trading & Kelly Criterion (for optimal capital allocation)
- Factor Investing: Value, Momentum, Low Volatility strategies

Resources:
- "Quantitative Trading" ‚Äì Ernest Chan
- Udacity - AI for Trading (Udacity)

### Machine Learning in Finance
Topics:
- Supervised Learning: Linear Regression, Decision Trees, Random Forests
- Unsupervised Learning: Clustering, PCA
- Gaussian Processes & Bayesian Statistics & Gaussian Processes for probabilistic forecasting
- Deep Reinforcement Learning (applied in trading & portfolio management)

Resources:
- "Advances in Financial Machine Learning" ‚Äì Marcos L√≥pez de Prado
- Coursera - Machine Learning by Andrew Ng (Coursera)

### Derivatives Pricing & Risk Management
Topics:
- Black-Scholes Model for Option Pricing (document)
- Greeks & Risk Measures (VaR, Conditional VaR) (document)
- Interest Rate Models (document)
- Stress Testing & Scenario Analysis (document)
- Jump-Diffusion Models (e.g., Merton Model for option pricing) (document)
- Stochastic Volatility Models (Heston Model, SABR) (document)

Resources:
- "Options, Futures & Other Derivatives" ‚Äì John Hull
- Coursera - Financial Engineering & Risk Management (Coursera)

---

## Advanced Level
### Portfolio Optimization

Portfolio Theory & Fundamentals
- Modern Portfolio Theory (MPT) ‚Üí Risk-return tradeoff, Efficient frontier
- Mean-Variance Optimization ‚Üí Markowitz model, Efficient frontier construction
- Risk-Return Measures ‚Üí Expected return, Standard deviation, Sharpe ratio, Sortino ratio
- Capital Market Theory ‚Üí Capital Market Line (CML), Security Market Line (SML)
- Asset Allocation Strategies ‚Üí Strategic vs. Tactical, Static vs. Dynamic allocationRisk Modeling & Factor Models
- Risk Parity & Portfolio Diversification ‚Üí Equal risk contribution, Minimum correlation
- Factor Models ‚Üí Fama-French (3, 5, or multi-factor), Arbitrage Pricing Theory (APT)
- Covariance Estimation & Shrinkage Methods ‚Üí Ledoit-Wolf shrinkage, Bayesian shrinkage
- Black-Litterman Model ‚Üí Bayesian asset allocation, Market equilibrium adjustmentsOptimization Techniques
- Quadratic Optimization ‚Üí Convex optimization, Lagrange multipliers
- Mean-CVaR (Conditional Value-at-Risk) Optimization ‚Üí Tail risk minimization
- Bayesian Portfolio Optimization ‚Üí Incorporating prior beliefs into asset allocation
- Robust Optimization ‚Üí Handling estimation errors in risk and return forecasts
- Multi-Objective Optimization ‚Üí Balancing different constraints like ESG, liquidityAlternative & Dynamic Portfolio Strategies
- Risk-Based Portfolios ‚Üí Minimum variance, Maximum diversification, Risk budgeting
- Hierarchical Risk Parity (HRP) ‚Üí Clustering-based asset allocation
- Momentum & Mean Reversion Strategies ‚Üí Time-series vs. cross-sectional momentum
- Adaptive Asset Allocation ‚Üí Regime-based investing, Dynamic rebalancing
- Kelly Criterion for Portfolio Sizing ‚Üí Optimal bet sizing based on probabilitiesMachine Learning & Advanced Topics
- Machine Learning in Portfolio Optimization ‚Üí Reinforcement learning, Genetic algorithms
- Deep Learning for Portfolio Management ‚Üí LSTMs, Autoencoders for factor analysis
- Monte Carlo Simulation in Portfolio Optimization ‚Üí Stochastic modeling for risk assessment
- Bayesian Networks & Probabilistic Graphical Models ‚Üí Causal inference in asset returnsResources:
- "Active Portfolio Management" ‚Äì Richard Grinold & Ronald Kahn
- Coursera - Portfolio and Risk Management (Coursera)

### Fixed Income Modeling

Bond Pricing & Yield Analysis
- Bond Pricing Fundamentals ‚Üí Present value, Discounting cash flows
- Yield to Maturity (YTM) & Spot Rates ‚Üí Measuring return for bonds
- Forward Rates & Yield Curve ‚Üí Constructing the term structure of interest ratesTerm Structure of Interest Rates
- Expectations Theory ‚Üí Future short-term rates drive long-term rates
- Liquidity Preference Theory ‚Üí Investors demand risk premiums for longer maturities
- Market Segmentation Theory ‚Üí Independent supply-demand forces for different maturities
- Yield Curve Modeling ‚Üí Nelson-Siegel, Svensson, and Vasicek modelsInterest Rate Models
- Vasicek Model ‚Üí Mean-reverting stochastic interest rates
- Cox-Ingersoll-Ross (CIR) Model ‚Üí Non-negative stochastic interest rates
- Hull-White Model ‚Üí Generalized short-rate model with time-varying volatility
- Heath-Jarrow-Morton (HJM) Framework ‚Üí Forward rate modeling for derivatives pricing
- Libor Market Model (LMM) ‚Üí Term structure evolution for interest rate derivativesDuration, Convexity & Hedging
- Macaulay & Modified Duration ‚Üí Sensitivity of bond prices to interest rates
- Key Rate Duration ‚Üí Interest rate risk at different maturities
- Convexity Adjustment ‚Üí Second-order price sensitivity to yield changes
- Immunization Strategies ‚Üí Hedging bond portfolios against interest rate changesCredit Spread & Risky Bonds
- Credit Spread Measurement ‚Üí Treasury vs. corporate bond spreads
- Credit Risk in Fixed Income ‚Üí Default probability, Recovery rates
- Merton Model for Default Risk ‚Üí Firm value-based credit risk assessmentFixed Income Derivatives & Structured Products
- Interest Rate Swaps ‚Üí Fixed vs. floating rate cash flow exchanges
- Caps, Floors & Collars ‚Üí Interest rate risk management derivatives
- Mortgage-Backed Securities (MBS) ‚Üí Securitization of mortgage loans
- Collateralized Debt Obligations (CDOs) ‚Üí Slicing credit risk exposure
- Convertible Bonds ‚Üí Hybrid securities with equity and debt characteristicsAdvanced Topics
- Machine Learning in Fixed Income ‚Üí Predictive modeling, Sentiment analysis on bond markets
- Bayesian Fixed Income Models ‚Üí Probabilistic bond pricing and risk estimation
- Stochastic Calculus in Fixed Income ‚Üí Ito‚Äôs Lemma, Jump diffusion models for bond pricing
- Deep Learning for Yield Curve Prediction ‚Üí LSTMs, Transformers for interest rate forecasting

### Credit Risk ModelingCredit Risk Fundamentals
- Probability of Default (PD) ‚Üí Estimating the likelihood of borrower default
- Loss Given Default (LGD) ‚Üí Measuring the severity of losses in default scenarios
- Exposure at Default (EAD) ‚Üí Estimating credit exposure at the time of default
- Credit Spread & Risky Bonds ‚Üí Measuring default risk through bond spreadsCredit Migration & Rating Models
- Credit Migration & Transition Matrices ‚Üí Markov chains, Credit rating transitions
- Credit Scoring Models ‚Üí Logistic regression, Machine learning, Moody‚Äôs, S&P ratings
- Altman Z-Score Model ‚Üí Financial distress prediction for corporate credit risk
- Machine Learning for Credit Scoring ‚Üí Decision trees, Neural networks, Gradient boostingStructural Credit Risk Models
- Merton Model ‚Üí Firm value-based credit risk assessment
- Black-Cox Model ‚Üí Barrier options framework for credit default prediction
- KMV Model ‚Üí EDF (Expected Default Frequency) estimation using firm volatilityReduced-Form Credit Risk Models
- Jarrow-Turnbull Model ‚Üí Intensity-based credit risk modeling
- Duffie-Singleton Model ‚Üí Hazard rate approach for credit default swaps (CDS) pricing
- Lando Model ‚Üí Extensions to intensity-based default risk modelingCredit Derivatives & Counterparty Risk
- Credit Default Swaps (CDS) ‚Üí Hedging credit risk with derivative contracts
- Collateralized Debt Obligations (CDOs) ‚Üí Securitization of credit risk exposure
- Credit Valuation Adjustments (CVA, DVA, FVA) ‚Üí Pricing counterparty credit risk
- Wrong-Way Risk & Right-Way Risk ‚Üí Correlation between exposure and default riskStress Testing & Regulatory Frameworks
- Basel III Credit Risk Capital Requirements ‚Üí Standardized vs. IRB approaches
- IFRS 9 & Expected Credit Loss (ECL) Model ‚Üí Financial reporting of credit risk
- Stress Testing & Scenario Analysis ‚Üí Sensitivity analysis for macroeconomic shocks

- Machine Learning for Credit Risk ‚Üí Predictive modeling, Feature engineering for credit scoring
- Bayesian Methods in Credit Risk ‚Üí Probabilistic models for default risk estimation
- Stochastic Calculus in Credit Derivatives ‚Üí Ito‚Äôs Lemma, Jump diffusion models
- Deep Learning for Default Prediction ‚Üí LSTMs, Autoencoders, Transformer-based modelsResources:
- "Fixed Income Securities" ‚Äì Bruce Tuckman
- DataCamp - Credit Risk Modeling in Python (DataCamp)

